So this leads me to kind of the first little thing that I wanted to mention on Reactivity and Shiny.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:02.000
And that's this reactive calc annotation.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:09.000
So basically what this allows us to do is when you're putting a lot of different visualizations on a screen.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:12.000
You oftentimes want to reuse pieces of code.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:13.000
Maybe you want to reuse variables.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:15.000
You want to reuse data frames, etc.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:20.000
But you don't want to have to like load those in each time that you need them.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:25.000
So this reactive calc basically will run an operation.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:27.000
And then it will return a value.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:32.000
And then that value is cached so that whenever you call it.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.000
So we're calling it here and we're calling it here.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:38.000
It's going to take that cached value and easily retrieve it.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:40.000
You'll get it really very quickly.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:41.000
So it helps with efficiency here.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:54.000
But one thing that I'd kind of recommend is I don't think it's great practice to directly modify that same data frame that is being called and created from the dat object.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:09:01.000
I kind of recommend that you either do everything in this dat function and then like everyone gets the updated data frame.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:06.000
Or if you wanted to just modify a data frame for one function specifically.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:15.000
I'd recommend copying the data frame so that the render plotly plot one up here wouldn't be affected by us adding a new month column to the data frame.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.000
That could cause problems in other situations.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:19.000
I don't think it would affect anything here.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:27.000
But it's just something to look out for that this calculates a value, caches it, and then we use that same value in multiple places.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:33.000
And if we wanted to modify that data frame, let's do it with a copy instead of the original that other properties will see.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:35.000
And we'll get into this in more detail.

